In 1877 Judd and his brother-in-law [[James_F._Broumton|James F. Broumton]] traveled through Hunan province to became the first Protestant Christian missionaries in [[Guiyang|Guiyang]], [[Guizhou|Guizhou]]. Broumton later pioneered work among the [[Miao|Miao]] and [[Yi_people|Yi people]] minority groups. Only the British explorer [[William_Mesny|William Mesny]] had attempted the introduction of Christianity earlier in Guizhou. While Broumton remained at Guiyang, Judd returned。

Adam Dorward and Judd traveled on an evangelistic journey 1500 miles across China from 1880-1882.

Judd left China again between 1885 and May 1887. He returned, then left again in May 1894.
Judd died in London, England, on 23 October 1919. Elizabeth Judd died in 1926.
They had several children: George H. Judd, Edwin Judd, Frederick Hudson Judd, and Ross Judd.<ref>Broomhall (1984), 448</ref>

